Rather than using `fill`, use `addAll` and `nCopies`:

```
if (items.size() &lt; 3) {
  items.addAll(Collections.nCopies(3 - items.size(), &quot;fallback&quot;));
}
```

As it says [in the Javadoc of `nCopies`](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/Collections.html#nCopies-int-T-):

&gt; This method is useful in combination with the List.addAll method to grow lists.

While you could combine together some provided functionality to achieve it, writing your own `fill` method seems the most straightforward to me:
```
private static void fill(List&lt;String&gt; list, String fallback) {
  if (list.size() &gt; 3) {
    //do something?
  }
  while (list.size() &lt; 3) {
    list.add(fallback);
  }
}
```
